{
  "doc_id": "32460",
  "text": "The present study on A2BAR signaling during renal ischemia is consistent with recent work on cardiac generation and signaling of adenosine [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For example, two recent studies provided genetic evidence for extracellular adenosine generation in cardio-protection by IP [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In extension of these findings, the authors compared preconditioning responses of gene-targeted mice for each individual AR. Consistent with the present studies and other studies on myocardial pre-or postconditioning [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , the authors found a pivotal role of the A2BAR, revealing that A2BAR agonist treatment preconditions the myocardium. Other investigations of renal ischemia and reperfusion injury have found contributions of the A2AAR [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . As such, a series of studies of renal ischemia and reperfusion in chimeric mice found that bone marrow-derived cells play an important role in A2AAR-mediated tissue protection [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Further work using adoptive transfers into Rag-1 À/À mice revealed that IFNc produced by CD4 þ T cells appears to be an important mediator for this complex interplay [CITATION_13] . Taken together with results from the present studies, these findings suggest a combined role of myeloid A2AARs-predominantly expressed on T-lymphocytes-and reno-vascular A2BARs in attenuation of renal ischemia.",
